WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.548
Hey, welcome back to the show. Today's a deep dive,

00:00:03.548 --> 00:00:07.096
and it's a fun one. We're talking about weekend cabins.

00:00:07.096 --> 00:00:10.644
Specifically, what does it actually look like to get a

00:00:10.644 --> 00:00:14.192
cabin or a piece of land within an hour or

00:00:14.192 --> 00:00:17.740
two of Jefferson City, Missouri? I spent a day going

00:00:17.740 --> 00:00:21.288
down this rabbit hole, looking at listings, crunching numbers, and

00:00:21.288 --> 00:00:24.836
mapping out the options. And I think you'll find the

00:00:24.836 --> 00:00:28.385
results pretty surprising. So let's start with the big picture.

00:00:28.385 --> 00:00:31.933
If you want a weekend getaway spot in central Missouri,

00:00:31.933 --> 00:00:35.481
you basically have three paths. You can buy an existing

00:00:35.481 --> 00:00:39.029
property. You can build something from scratch. Or you can

00:00:39.029 --> 00:00:42.577
do a hybrid approach, which is actually my favorite, and

00:00:42.577 --> 00:00:46.125
I'll explain why later. But first, let me walk you

00:00:46.125 --> 00:00:49.673
through the target areas, because Missouri has some genuinely great

00:00:49.673 --> 00:00:53.221
options that a lot of people overlook. The most obvious

00:00:53.221 --> 00:00:56.769
one is Lake of the Ozarks. It's about an hour

00:00:56.769 --> 00:01:00.317
from Jeff City, and it's the big draw for a

00:01:00.317 --> 00:01:03.865
reason. You've got lake access, you've got restaurants and marinas

00:01:03.865 --> 00:01:07.413
nearby, and there's a whole ecosystem of weekend-friendly stuff. But

00:01:07.413 --> 00:01:10.961
the prices reflect that. It's the most expensive option on

00:01:10.961 --> 00:01:14.509
this list. Then you've got the Southern Ozarks and Mark

00:01:14.509 --> 00:01:18.057
Twain National Forest area, which is about an hour and

00:01:18.057 --> 00:01:21.605
a half to two hours south. This is where it

00:01:21.605 --> 00:01:25.154
gets really interesting for people on a budget. We're talking

00:01:25.154 --> 00:01:28.702
deep woods, rolling hills, rivers and streams, and land prices

00:01:28.702 --> 00:01:32.250
that will make your jaw drop. I found twenty-acre parcels

00:01:32.250 --> 00:01:35.798
near Ellington for thirty thousand dollars. Twenty acres. That's fifteen

00:01:35.798 --> 00:01:39.346
hundred bucks an acre for gorgeous Ozark forest land. Third

00:01:39.346 --> 00:01:42.894
option is Hermann and the Missouri wine country corridor, about

00:01:42.894 --> 00:01:46.442
an hour east. This is more of a charming small-town

00:01:46.442 --> 00:01:49.990
vibe. Rolling vineyards, little bed and breakfasts, great food scene.

00:01:49.990 --> 00:01:53.538
Not as rustic as the Ozarks, but really pleasant for

00:01:53.538 --> 00:01:57.086
a different kind of weekend. And then there's Thousand Hills

00:01:57.086 --> 00:02:00.634
State Park area, about two hours north near Kirksville. Beautiful

00:02:00.634 --> 00:02:04.182
lake, great hiking, and it's the least crowded option by

00:02:04.182 --> 00:02:07.730
far. The trade-off is it's the longest drive. OK, so

00:02:07.730 --> 00:02:11.278
let's talk about what's actually on the market right now,

00:02:11.278 --> 00:02:14.826
because I went deep on Zillow and some other listing

00:02:14.826 --> 00:02:18.374
sites, and there's some really compelling stuff. Near Lake of

00:02:18.374 --> 00:02:21.923
the Ozarks, you can find small homes, we're talking one

00:02:21.923 --> 00:02:25.471
or two bedrooms, ranging from about fifteen thousand dollars up

00:02:25.471 --> 00:02:29.019
to around a hundred and forty thousand. Now, the fifteen

00:02:29.019 --> 00:02:32.567
thousand dollar places? They need work. But they exist. And

00:02:32.567 --> 00:02:36.115
at the lake, even a fixer-upper has value because of

00:02:36.115 --> 00:02:39.663
the location. The standout listing I found was a thirty-nine

00:02:39.663 --> 00:02:43.211
thousand dollar one-bedroom cabin with dock access. Let me say

00:02:43.211 --> 00:02:46.759
that again. Thirty-nine K for a cabin on the lake

00:02:46.759 --> 00:02:50.307
with dock access. Is it fancy? No. Is it a

00:02:50.307 --> 00:02:53.855
weekend cabin where you can wake up, walk down to

00:02:53.855 --> 00:02:57.403
the dock, and go fishing? Absolutely. Now, if you're thinking

00:02:57.403 --> 00:03:00.951
about building instead, let's talk about land. Near Edwards, Missouri,

00:03:00.951 --> 00:03:04.499
which is in the Lake of the Ozarks area, I

00:03:04.499 --> 00:03:08.047
found wooded lots of two to three acres going for

00:03:08.047 --> 00:03:11.595
five to six thousand dollars. Five to six thousand. For

00:03:11.595 --> 00:03:15.144
your own piece of wooded Missouri land. That's, honestly, kind

00:03:15.144 --> 00:03:18.692
of wild. If you want more space and more seclusion,

00:03:18.692 --> 00:03:22.240
the Mark Twain National Forest area is incredible. I found

00:03:22.240 --> 00:03:25.788
a twenty-acre parcel near Ellington for thirty thousand, and an

00:03:25.788 --> 00:03:29.336
eleven-acre parcel near Raymondville for forty-five thousand. These are bigger

00:03:29.336 --> 00:03:32.884
parcels with real privacy, surrounded by national forest land, so

00:03:32.884 --> 00:03:36.432
your neighbors are basically deer and turkey. OK. So this

00:03:36.432 --> 00:03:39.980
brings us to the build option, which I want to

00:03:39.980 --> 00:03:43.528
break down in detail because I think a lot of

00:03:43.528 --> 00:03:47.076
people assume building is way out of reach, and in

00:03:47.076 --> 00:03:50.624
Missouri? It's actually surprisingly doable. And here's the kicker that

00:03:50.624 --> 00:03:54.172
makes Missouri special: there is no statewide building code. Many

00:03:54.172 --> 00:03:57.720
rural counties have minimal or no code enforcement at all.

00:03:57.720 --> 00:04:01.268
That means you can build a simple cabin without navigating

00:04:01.268 --> 00:04:04.816
a mountain of permits and inspections. I'm not saying you

00:04:04.816 --> 00:04:08.364
should build something unsafe. I'm saying the regulatory burden is

00:04:08.364 --> 00:04:11.913
dramatically lower than most states. So let's walk through what

00:04:11.913 --> 00:04:15.461
a D-I-Y cabin build actually costs, piece by piece. Foundation.

00:04:15.461 --> 00:04:19.009
For a small cabin, you're looking at a concrete pier

00:04:19.009 --> 00:04:22.557
or post foundation, which runs about two to four thousand

00:04:22.557 --> 00:04:26.105
dollars in materials. This is the simplest approach and it's

00:04:26.105 --> 00:04:29.653
perfect for a weekend place. Framing and structure. If you're

00:04:29.653 --> 00:04:33.201
doing a basic cabin, maybe six hundred square feet, you're

00:04:33.201 --> 00:04:36.749
looking at framing lumber and materials in the eight to

00:04:36.749 --> 00:04:40.297
twelve thousand dollar range, depending on lumber prices. You can

00:04:40.297 --> 00:04:43.845
bring this down further if you go with a kit

00:04:43.845 --> 00:04:47.393
cabin from a company like Jamaica Cottage Shop, which ships

00:04:47.393 --> 00:04:50.941
pre-cut framing packages. Roofing. Metal roofing is the way to

00:04:50.941 --> 00:04:54.489
go for a cabin. It's durable, low maintenance, and runs

00:04:54.489 --> 00:04:58.037
about three to five thousand for a small structure. It'll

00:04:58.037 --> 00:05:01.585
last thirty to fifty years with basically zero upkeep. Now

00:05:01.585 --> 00:05:05.133
here's where it gets really interesting. Water. If you're on

00:05:05.133 --> 00:05:08.682
rural land, you need a well. Well drilling in Missouri

00:05:08.682 --> 00:05:12.230
typically runs twenty-five hundred to ninety-seven hundred dollars, depending on

00:05:12.230 --> 00:05:15.778
depth. The Ozarks can be tricky because of the rock,

00:05:15.778 --> 00:05:19.326
but most areas you'll hit water within a hundred to

00:05:19.326 --> 00:05:22.874
two hundred feet. Alternatively, for a weekend-only cabin, some people

00:05:22.874 --> 00:05:26.422
just use a large water tank that they fill up

00:05:26.422 --> 00:05:29.970
each visit, but a well is obviously the better long-term

00:05:29.970 --> 00:05:33.518
play. Kitchen. For a simple cabin kitchen, you're looking at

00:05:33.518 --> 00:05:37.066
two to four thousand. A basic sink, a propane stove,

00:05:37.066 --> 00:05:40.614
some countertop and cabinet space. You don't need granite countertops.

00:05:40.614 --> 00:05:44.162
You need something that works. Electricity. This is where you've

00:05:44.162 --> 00:05:47.710
got a real choice. Solar with battery storage runs about

00:05:47.710 --> 00:05:51.258
two to five thousand for a basic off-grid setup that

00:05:51.258 --> 00:05:54.806
can handle lights, charging, and a small fridge. Grid connection,

00:05:54.806 --> 00:05:58.354
if it's available and close to the road, can actually

00:05:58.354 --> 00:06:01.903
be cheaper upfront, but you'll have a monthly bill. For

00:06:01.903 --> 00:06:05.451
a weekend cabin, solar with a battery bank is honestly

00:06:05.451 --> 00:06:08.999
ideal. You're not running air conditioning. You're running lights, a

00:06:08.999 --> 00:06:12.547
phone charger, and maybe a mini fridge. Heating. Wood stove.

00:06:12.547 --> 00:06:16.095
Period. A good wood stove runs five hundred to fifteen

00:06:16.095 --> 00:06:19.643
hundred dollars. Installation maybe another five hundred. And you're surrounded

00:06:19.643 --> 00:06:23.191
by trees. Your fuel is literally on the ground around

00:06:23.191 --> 00:06:26.739
you. A wood stove also adds a huge amount of

00:06:26.739 --> 00:06:30.287
ambiance to a cabin. There's nothing like waking up on

00:06:30.287 --> 00:06:33.835
a cold morning, getting a fire going, and making coffee

00:06:33.835 --> 00:06:37.383
while looking out at the woods. Now, the bathroom situation.

00:06:37.383 --> 00:06:40.931
This is where you can save a surprising amount of

00:06:40.931 --> 00:06:44.479
money. A full septic system runs five to ten thousand

00:06:44.479 --> 00:06:48.027
dollars, and it requires engineering and permits even in lenient

00:06:48.027 --> 00:06:51.575
counties. But a composting toilet? We're talking three hundred to

00:06:51.575 --> 00:06:55.123
eight hundred dollars, and no septic system needed at all.

00:06:55.123 --> 00:06:58.672
Modern composting toilets are honestly not bad. They don't smell

00:06:58.672 --> 00:07:02.220
if you maintain them, and for a weekend cabin, they're

00:07:02.220 --> 00:07:05.768
perfectly adequate. Add a simple outdoor shower with a solar

00:07:05.768 --> 00:07:09.316
shower bag for summer, and maybe a small on-demand propane

00:07:09.316 --> 00:07:12.864
water heater for colder months, and you've got a functioning

00:07:12.864 --> 00:07:16.412
bathroom for a fraction of the cost. And finally, I'd

00:07:16.412 --> 00:07:19.960
budget for a covered porch. Because what's the point of

00:07:19.960 --> 00:07:23.508
a cabin without a porch? Figure another two to three

00:07:23.508 --> 00:07:27.056
thousand for a nice covered porch where you can sit

00:07:27.056 --> 00:07:30.604
in the evening and watch the fireflies. So let's add

00:07:30.604 --> 00:07:34.152
this all up. A budget D-I-Y build on a five

00:07:34.152 --> 00:07:37.700
to six thousand dollar lot comes in around thirty-five to

00:07:37.700 --> 00:07:41.248
forty thousand dollars total. That gets you a basic but

00:07:41.248 --> 00:07:44.796
solid cabin with solar power, a composting toilet, a wood

00:07:44.796 --> 00:07:48.344
stove, and a well. If you want to step it

00:07:48.344 --> 00:07:51.892
up to a moderate build with full utilities, meaning grid

00:07:51.892 --> 00:07:55.441
power, a real septic system, a proper bathroom with running

00:07:55.441 --> 00:07:58.989
water and a flush toilet, you're looking at about seventy-five

00:07:58.989 --> 00:08:02.537
to eighty-five thousand on a fifteen to thirty thousand dollar

00:08:02.537 --> 00:08:06.085
piece of land. Here's what I think is the most

00:08:06.085 --> 00:08:09.633
interesting finding from all this research. When you run the

00:08:09.633 --> 00:08:13.181
numbers over a five-year time horizon, buying and building end

00:08:13.181 --> 00:08:16.729
up costing roughly the same. That total five-year cost, including

00:08:16.729 --> 00:08:20.277
purchase price or build costs, maintenance, property tax, insurance, everything,

00:08:20.277 --> 00:08:23.825
lands in the forty-five to one hundred and five thousand

00:08:23.825 --> 00:08:27.373
dollar range for both paths. The difference is really about

00:08:27.373 --> 00:08:30.921
what you want and when you want it. Speaking of

00:08:30.921 --> 00:08:34.469
property tax, I have to mention this because it's kind

00:08:34.469 --> 00:08:38.017
of amazing. Property tax on rural Missouri land is almost

00:08:38.017 --> 00:08:41.565
negligible. We're talking fifty to eighty dollars a year for

00:08:41.565 --> 00:08:45.113
undeveloped land. Even with a small cabin on it, you're

00:08:45.113 --> 00:08:48.662
probably looking at a few hundred dollars a year. Compare

00:08:48.662 --> 00:08:52.210
that to property taxes in other states and it's just

00:08:52.210 --> 00:08:55.758
laughably low. Now, let me talk about the build timeline,

00:08:55.758 --> 00:08:59.306
because this is where people's eyes get bigger than their

00:08:59.306 --> 00:09:02.854
stomachs. If you're a weekend warrior builder, meaning you're going

00:09:02.854 --> 00:09:06.402
out every weekend or every other weekend to work on

00:09:06.402 --> 00:09:09.950
it, a realistic timeline for a basic cabin is twelve

00:09:09.950 --> 00:09:13.498
to eighteen months. And honestly? Plan for eighteen to twenty-four.

00:09:13.498 --> 00:09:17.046
Things always take longer than you think. Weather delays, supply

00:09:17.046 --> 00:09:20.594
chain hiccups, that weekend you just really didn't feel like

00:09:20.594 --> 00:09:24.142
driving an hour to pour concrete. It happens. Build that

00:09:24.142 --> 00:09:27.690
cushion into your expectations. On the kit cabin front, I

00:09:27.690 --> 00:09:31.238
looked at Jamaica Cottage Shop, which is a popular option.

00:09:31.238 --> 00:09:34.786
They ship pre-cut timber frame cabin kits that you assemble

00:09:34.786 --> 00:09:38.334
on-site. The kits themselves run ten to twenty thousand depending

00:09:38.334 --> 00:09:41.882
on size, and they dramatically simplify the framing process. You

00:09:41.882 --> 00:09:45.431
still need to do the foundation, roofing, and interior yourself,

00:09:45.431 --> 00:09:48.979
but the structural work is way more approachable. Another creative

00:09:48.979 --> 00:09:52.527
option is a Tuff Shed conversion. You buy a large

00:09:52.527 --> 00:09:56.075
Tuff Shed, which runs three to five thousand, and then

00:09:56.075 --> 00:09:59.623
finish the interior yourself. It's not as romantic as a

00:09:59.623 --> 00:10:03.171
timber frame cabin, but it's fast and cheap. Some people

00:10:03.171 --> 00:10:06.719
use these as a starter structure while they build their

00:10:06.719 --> 00:10:10.267
real cabin nearby. Now here's my actual recommendation, and this

00:10:10.267 --> 00:10:13.815
is where I think the real value is. The hybrid

00:10:13.815 --> 00:10:17.363
approach. Here's what I'd do. Step one: buy a cheap

00:10:17.363 --> 00:10:20.911
lake property in the twenty-five to forty thousand dollar range.

00:10:20.911 --> 00:10:24.459
That thirty-nine thousand dollar cabin with dock access? That's your

00:10:24.459 --> 00:10:28.007
immediate play. You can use it this weekend. You've got

00:10:28.007 --> 00:10:31.555
a place to go. Step two: start scoping land for

00:10:31.555 --> 00:10:35.103
a future build. Go visit those five to six thousand

00:10:35.103 --> 00:10:38.651
dollar lots near Edwards. Go hike the twenty-acre parcel near

00:10:38.651 --> 00:10:42.200
Ellington. Take your time with this. Feel different properties in

00:10:42.200 --> 00:10:45.748
different seasons. There's no rush because you already have your

00:10:45.748 --> 00:10:49.296
weekend place. Step three: over the next year or two,

00:10:49.296 --> 00:10:52.844
start planning and maybe even beginning your build on the

00:10:52.844 --> 00:10:56.392
land you've chosen. You can store materials there. You can

00:10:56.392 --> 00:10:59.940
camp there while you work. And your existing cabin gives

00:10:59.940 --> 00:11:03.488
you a comfortable home base for weekend build trips. This

00:11:03.488 --> 00:11:07.036
approach gives you the best of both worlds. Immediate gratification

00:11:07.036 --> 00:11:10.584
and long-term potential. You're not waiting eighteen months for your

00:11:10.584 --> 00:11:14.132
first weekend in the woods. You're going this weekend. And

00:11:14.132 --> 00:11:17.680
the build project becomes a fun, low-pressure hobby rather than

00:11:17.680 --> 00:11:21.228
a desperate race to get a roof over your head.

00:11:21.228 --> 00:11:24.776
So let me do a quick summary of the standout

00:11:24.776 --> 00:11:28.324
listings. Number one: that thirty-nine thousand dollar one-bedroom cabin with

00:11:28.324 --> 00:11:31.872
dock access near the lake. Best immediate value for a

00:11:31.872 --> 00:11:35.421
weekend escape. Number two: the five to six thousand dollar

00:11:35.421 --> 00:11:38.969
wooded lots near Edwards. Incredible for anyone who wants to

00:11:38.969 --> 00:11:42.517
build. Number three: twenty acres near Ellington for thirty thousand

00:11:42.517 --> 00:11:46.065
dollars. If you want seclusion and space, this is your

00:11:46.065 --> 00:11:49.613
move. And number four: eleven acres near Raymondville for forty-five

00:11:49.613 --> 00:11:53.161
thousand, which is a larger investment but gets you a

00:11:53.161 --> 00:11:56.709
serious piece of land near Mark Twain National Forest. So

00:11:56.709 --> 00:12:00.257
bottom line. A weekend cabin in Missouri is way more

00:12:00.257 --> 00:12:03.805
accessible than most people think. You can be in the

00:12:03.805 --> 00:12:07.353
game for as little as fifteen to twenty thousand dollars

00:12:07.353 --> 00:12:10.901
with a fixer-upper, or five to six thousand if you

00:12:10.901 --> 00:12:14.449
just want to start with land and camp while you

00:12:14.449 --> 00:12:17.997
build. The sweet spot for most people is probably that

00:12:17.997 --> 00:12:21.545
twenty-five to fifty thousand dollar range, which gets you either

00:12:21.545 --> 00:12:25.093
a turnkey small cabin or a piece of land with

00:12:25.093 --> 00:12:28.641
a budget build. Missouri's combination of low land prices, almost

00:12:28.641 --> 00:12:32.190
nonexistent property taxes, no statewide building code, and genuinely beautiful

00:12:32.190 --> 00:12:35.738
Ozark terrain makes it one of the best states in

00:12:35.738 --> 00:12:39.286
the country for this kind of project. If you've been

00:12:39.286 --> 00:12:42.834
daydreaming about a weekend cabin, the numbers say it's more

00:12:42.834 --> 00:12:46.382
doable than you might think. That's it for today's deep

00:12:46.382 --> 00:12:49.930
dive. If you found this useful, I'd love to hear

00:12:49.930 --> 00:12:53.478
about it. And if you end up looking at any

00:12:53.478 --> 00:12:57.026
of these listings, let me know what you find. Until

00:12:57.026 --> 00:12:58.800
next time, happy cabin hunting.
